06235nam a22009375i 9780674063266DE-B159720190708092533.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||190708s2012    mau    fo  d z      eng d  a97806740632667 a10.4159/harvard.97806740632662doi  a(DE-B1597)178131  a(OCoLC)979746653  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  amaucUS-MA 7aHIS0160002bisacsh04a945.0072022211 aIanziti, Gary, eauthor.10aWriting History in Renaissance Italy :bLeonardo Bruni and the Uses of the Past /cGary Ianziti. 1aCambridge, MA : bHarvard University Press, c[2012] 4cÂ©2011  a1 online resource   atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aI Tatti Studies in Italian Renaissance History00t Frontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- t1. Bruni on Writing History -- tPart one. Beginnings -- t2. The Plutarchan Option -- t3. A New Life of Cicero -- t4. Between Livy and Polybius: Bruni on the First Punic War -- tPart two. Florence under the Oligarchy -- t5. Genesis of the Florentine Histories -- t6. The Florentine Histories: A Sourcebook for Statesmen -- t7. Bruni and Biography: A Life of Aristotle -- tPart three. Medici Florence -- t8. Parallel Lives: Dante and Petrarch -- t9. Bruni, the Medici, and the Florentine Histories -- t10. The Florentine Histories: From Policy to Propaganda -- tPart four. Late Works -- t11. A Distant Mirror: Athens, Sparta, and Thebes -- t12. Memoirs of a Humanist -- t13. Writing from Procopius -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aLeonardo Bruni (1370-1444) is widely recognized as the most important humanist historian of the early Renaissance. But why this recognition came about-and what it has meant for the field of historiography-has long been a matter of confusion and controversy. Writing History in Renaissance Italy offers a fresh approach to the subject by undertaking a systematic, work-by-work investigation that encompasses for the first time the full range of Bruni's output in history and biography.The study is the first to assess in detail the impact of the classical Greek historians on the development of humanist methods of historical writing. It highlights in particular the importance of Thucydides and Polybius-authors Bruni was among the first in the West to read, and whose analytical approach to politics led him in new directions. Yet the revolution in history that unfolds across the four decades covered in this study is no mere revival of classical models: Ianziti constantly monitors Bruni's position within the shifting hierarchies of power in Florence, drawing connections between his various historical works and the political uses they were meant to serve.The result is a clearer picture of what Bruni hoped to achieve, and a more precise analysis of the dynamics driving his new approach to the past. Bruni himself emerges as a protagonist of the first order, a figure whose location at the center of power was a decisive factor shaping his innovations in historical writing.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 08. Jul 2019) 0aBiographerszItalyzFlorencevBiography. 0aHistorianszItalyzFlorencevBiography. 0aHistoriographyzItalyzFlorencexHistoryyTo 1500. 0aHumanistszItalyzFlorencevBiography. 0aRenaissancezItalyzFlorencexHistoriography. 7aHISTORY / Historiography.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertE-BOOK GESAMTPAKET / COMPLETE PACKAGE 2012z9783110288995oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertE-BOOK PACKAGE HISTORY; POLITICAL SCIENCE, SOCIOLOGY  2012z978311029371508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertE-BOOK PAKET GESCHICHTE, POLITIKWISS., SOZIOLOGIE  2012z9783110288971oZDB-23-DPS08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe G